### Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a user by ID from the REST API.")]
    public async Task<string> GetUser(
        [Description("The numeric user ID")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching user {UserId}", userId);
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users/{userId}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new user with the given name and email.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateUser(
        [Description("Full name of the user")] string name,
        [Description("Email address")] string email,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, email });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");

        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/users", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = true), Description("Search users by name substring.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchUsers(
        [Description("Name fragment to search for")] string query,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/users?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}", cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in the constructor (like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`) |
| **Method parameter injection** | Static class | DI services as method params alongside tool params |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from injected services. Parameters with `[Description]` appear in the tool's JSON schema (visible to the LLM). Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, and `IProgress<T>` are **resolved from DI and never exposed** in the schema.

In the example above, `ApiTools` uses a **non-static class with constructor injection** — the recommended pattern when multiple tools share the same dependencies. The `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected via the primary constructor, while `userId`, `name`, `email`, and `query` are the LLM-visible parameters.

Register services in `Program.cs` before `AddMcpServer()`:
- `AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(...)` — typed `HttpClient` with a base address
- `ILogger<T>` — registered automatically by the host builder
